.HEADING 1 "Configuration"
.PP
Dotfiles and settings files are located in \f(CW~/.config/\fP.
.PP
Suckless programs\(endwm (the window manager), st (the terminal), and dmenu\(endo not have traditional config files.
Their source code lives in \f(CW~/.local/src/\fP.
There you can modify their \f(CWconfig.h\fP files or other source code, then run \f(CWsudo make install\fP to reinstall.
.PP
vim/nvim is set to automatically recompile and install suckless programs whenever you save changes to a \f(CWconfig.h\fP file
(compilation is nearly instantaneous).
You'll need to restart the program to see changes take effect.
.PP
The \fBdotfiles\fP are managed with GNU \fBstow\fP, with the repo living in \f(CW~/.local/src/dotfiles/\fP.
Most configuration customization can be done by editing files there.
.PP
Directory and file \fBbookmarks\fP are managed via \f(CW~/.config/shell/bm-dirs\fP and \f(CWbm-files\fP.
Run the \f(CWshortcuts\fP script after editing them to regenerate per-program configs (this also happens automatically on login).
.HEADING 1 "Frequently Asked Questions (FAQs)"
.HEADING 2 "My keyboard isn't working as expected!"
.PP
As mentioned above, CARBS makes keyboard changes with the \f(CWremaps\fP script.
These settings may override your preferences, so open this file and comment out troublesome lines if you have issues.
The script is located at \f(CW~/.local/bin/remaps\fP and is run automatically on login.
You can rerun it at any time with \f(CWMod+F12\fP.
.HEADING 2 "My audio isn't working!"
.PP
On fresh installs, the Linux audio system often mutes outputs.
This system uses \fBPipeWire\fP for audio.
You can check and set your preferred output with \f(CWpulsemixer\fP (\f(CWMod+F4\fP) or \f(CWwpctl status\fP in the terminal.
.HEADING 2 "How do I copy and paste?"
.PP
Copying and pasting is always program-specific.
In most graphical programs, copy and paste are the same as on Windows: \f(CWctrl-c\fP and \f(CWctrl-v\fP.
In the terminal, those bindings have other purposes; run \f(CWman st\fP to see how to copy and paste in the terminal.
.PP
vim is set to use the system clipboard as the default buffer, so yanking or deleting in vim puts the text in your clipboard for pasting into any other program.
You can also paste material from other programs into vim with the usual vim paste bindings.
.HEADING 2 "How do I change the background/wallpaper?"
.PP
The system reads \f(CW~/.local/share/bg\fP as the wallpaper.
The script \f(CWsetbg\fP, when run on an image, sets it as the persistent background.
When using the file manager, hover over an image and press \f(CWb\fP to run \f(CWsetbg\fP.
.PP
If \fBpywal\fP is installed (it is, as \f(CWpython-pywal16\fP), \f(CWsetbg\fP will automatically generate a colorscheme from the wallpaper and apply it system-wide.
.HEADING 2 "How do I change the colorscheme?"
.PP
This system uses \fBpywal16\fP to generate colorschemes from your wallpaper automatically.
Setting a new wallpaper with \f(CWsetbg\fP (or by pressing \f(CWb\fP in the file manager) will generate and apply a new scheme immediately.
.PP
You can also find color schemes in \f(CW~/.config/wal/colorschemes/\fP,
or edit \f(CW~/.config/x11/xresources\fP for manual overrides.
Press \f(CWMod+F5\fP to reload Xresources and apply changes live without restarting.
.HEADING 2 "How do I set up my email?"
.PP
CARBS includes \fBmutt-wizard\fP, which lets you receive and send email from the terminal
and keeps an offline store without needing a browser.
Add an email account by running \f(CWmw -a your@email.com\fP.
See \f(CWman mw\fP for full details.
.PP
Once configured, open mail with \f(CWneomutt\fP (also bound to \f(CWMod+e\fP).
Sync mail with \f(CWMod+F8\fP, or set a cronjob to sync every 10 minutes with \f(CWmw -t 10\fP.
.HEADING 2 "How do I manage passwords?"
.PP
CARBS uses \fBKeePassXC\fP for password management.
You can open the KeePassXC GUI via the scratchpad at \f(CWMod+\\\fP.
The \fBkeepmenu\fP tool (bound to \f(CWMod+Shift+d\fP and \f(CWMod+Shift+\\\fP) provides dmenu-driven access to your KeePass database for quickly copying passwords without opening the full GUI.
.HEADING 2 "How do I set up my music?"
.PP
By default, \fBmpd\fP assumes \f(CW~/Music\fP is your music directory.
This can be changed in \f(CW~/.config/mpd/mpd.conf\fP.
When you add music to your music folder, run \f(CWmpc up\fP in the terminal to update the database.
mpd is controlled by \fBncmpcpp\fP, accessible at \f(CWMod+m\fP.
.HEADING 2 "How do I update CARBS?"
.PP
The dotfiles are a git repository at \f(CW~/.local/src/dotfiles/\fP.
You can use git to fetch, diff, and merge changes from the remote repository.
The suckless programs (dwm, st, dmenu, dwmblocks) each live in their own repo under \f(CW~/.local/src/\fP and can be updated the same way: pull the latest changes and run \f(CWsudo make install\fP.
.PP
You can also rerun the CARBS install script to do a full refresh, which will reinstall all packages and reapply the dotfiles (this will overwrite any local changes to tracked config files).
.HEADING 1 "Important Links"
.PP
You can follow links via the keyboard in this pdf reader by pressing \f(CWf\fP followed by the number that appears on the desired link.
.LI
.ITEM
.PDF_WWW_LINK "https://github.com/corbin-zip" "github.com/corbin-zip"
\(en Source code for dwm, st, dmenu, dwmblocks, and CARBS
.ITEM
.PDF_WWW_LINK "https://github.com/corbin-zip/CARBS" "github.com/corbin-zip/CARBS"
\(en The CARBS install script
.LIST OFF
